from under us. Trump doesn’t want the federal government to coordinate a national response to the public health emergency because he knows the public will hold the federal government accountable for the inevitable breakdown of the healthcare system. By claiming that the

governors are in charge, Trump is reserving the right to criticize the governors for the collapse of the healthcare system Meanwhile, Trump is busily trying to re-write history by claiming that no one could have anticipated an epidemic in the US. No one is buying his revisionist

history. See Op-ed by Greg Sargent in Washington Post, “Trump’s effort to bury the truth about his coronavirus fiasco is failing.” Trump gave a jaw-dropping interview to Sean Hannity on Thursday evening. In the interview, Trump suggested that whiny state governors were

exaggerating the problem to get medical equipment they didn’t really need. See The Daily Beast, “Trump: I Don’t Think Governors ‘Need’ the Medical Equipment They’re Begging For.” Among other mind-boggling statements, Trump told Hannity, I have a feeling that a lot of the

numbers that are being said in some areas are just bigger than they are going to be. I don’t believe you need 40,000 or 30,000 ventilators. You know, you go to major hospitals, sometimes they have 2 ventilators. Trump’s comments betray a level of ignorance that is breathtaking.

The number of ventilators that some “major hospitals” have is irrelevant to the question of how many ventilators hospitals will need during a pandemic. As NY Governor Andrew Cuomo explained on Thursday morning, Covid-19 patients require ventilators for extended periods—ranging up

to 21 days. See CNN, “New York will allow two patients to share a single ventilator.” New York has only 4,000 ventilators on hand now, with 4,000 more coming from the federal government. Regardless of what Trump “feels” about the progress of the pandemic, Governor Cuomo based
his request on projections that incorporate the facts on the ground in New York.

@andrewrsorkin @beckyquick @realdonaldtrump @SquawkCNBC Trump’s effort to re-open the economy on a county-by-county basis is flawed. The Los Angeles Times addressed Trump’s effort to prematurely re-open the economy in its editorial, “The most important thing is to contain COVID-

19. Then we can think about going back to work.” The Times editorial recognizes the key role that testing must play in re-opening the economy. If we really want to start getting back to normal, we would need to know who has the disease and where they are, which means testing

everyone regardless of symptoms on a regular basis; checking the temperature of people as they enter offices, apartments and stores; rapidly isolating those who show signs of the disease; and providing protective equipment not just to first responders and healthcare workers, but

also to every person who ventures out in public. To implement the strategy discussed in the Times editorial, the US needs the ability to identify those who have been infected by the virus. Fortunately, seventeen companies have notified the FDA that they are working on antibody

tests to identify those who have been infected with the virus that causes Covid-19. See ABC News, “Blood tests could help battle COVID-19 in US.” The blood tests could be available in several weeks. That is hopeful news, indeed. Meanwhile, Trump continues to mismanage the federal

response. Trump has told states to “buy it themselves” when it comes to medical supplies. But when states try to “buy it themselves,” they find themselves in bidding wars with other states and the federal government. See Louisville Courier-Journal, “Gerth: Trump has us fighting
